    <pre>As suggested by Carol, the readthedocs index page could be linked to more 
prominently from openhatch.org.  Although that raises general issues about how 
the homepage is designed and what is highlighted/left in small text at the bottom 
of the page.</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
 
  <tr>
   <th><a href="msg3928">msg3928 (view)</a></th>
   <th>Author: shauna</th>
   <th>Date: 2013-11-06.00:31:23</th>
   <th>
    
   </th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>I'd like to improve the landing pages for OH-mainline documentation.  This would 
include:

- The readthedocs index page (<a href="http://openhatch.readthedocs.org/en/latest/index.html">http://openhatch.readthedocs.org/en/latest/index.html</a>): Should be more verbose 
(at least full sentences!) and highlight the most common/important part of the 
documentation.  Make sure to include a section on "how to navigate this 
documentation".  Should link to any key non-documentation aspects of OH.

- Make sure the README in oh-mainline main directory 
(<a href="https://github.com/openhatch/oh-">https://github.com/openhatch/oh-</a>
mainline/blob/e485c8d98d5b7386ecf436526305e930ac25e4ad/README.rst) and the 
README in the docs directory (<a href="https://github.com/openhatch/oh-">https://github.com/openhatch/oh-</a>
mainline/blob/e485c8d98d5b7386ecf436526305e930ac25e4ad/docs/README.rst) are 
intelligible and link to the readthedocs landing page directly. 

For all of the above, make sure all links go where intended.  (For instance 
clicking ":doc:`deployment/installation`" in the /docs/README.rst brings you 
nowhere.)</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
